 They have 2 different use cases really, although a solution can often use one or the other. An if statement is more about flow control while a case/switch is more aimed at identifying data.

If I need to check a single condition then I would use an if statement, I can then break or return the flow and have clean code after it for the false case. 

It's also alot nicer to read this:

    var d = 1;

    if(d == 1){
    return "Is one";
    }

    return "is not one";
